[MUSIC]

00:01:12.509 --> 00:01:20.616
[APPLAUSE]

00:01:20.616 --> 00:01:26.902
&gt;&gt; Mr.President, as faculty marshal, I have the honor to declare the 120th commencement of

00:01:26.902 --> 00:01:32.547
Carnegie Mellon University, as authorized
by the trustees, to be in session.

00:01:32.547 --> 00:01:35.725
&gt;&gt; [APPLAUSE]

00:01:35.725 --> 00:01:45.725
[MUSIC]

00:01:57.442 --> 00:01:58.414
&gt;&gt; Please rise for

00:01:58.414 --> 00:02:03.438
the singing of our national anthem by
the vocal performance class of 2017.

00:02:09.399 --> 00:02:19.399
&gt;&gt; [MUSIC]

00:03:48.241 --> 00:03:54.683
&gt;&gt; [APPLAUSE]

00:04:11.665 --> 00:04:12.722
&gt;&gt; Good morning.

00:04:15.825 --> 00:04:23.760
We are gathered in a wonderful place of
collaborative study, work and living.

00:04:23.760 --> 00:04:25.980
Please be seated.

00:04:25.980 --> 00:04:31.600
&gt;&gt; [APPLAUSE]

00:04:31.760 --> 00:04:38.400
&gt;&gt; Together, all of us, we are diverse in our
fields of study, our talents and

00:04:38.400 --> 00:04:43.220
our abilities, our ethnicities and
the places that we call home.

00:04:44.620 --> 00:04:49.660
In light of a respect for others,
and with an acknowledgement

00:04:49.661 --> 00:04:54.705
of our differences,
I invite you to join me, if you are able,

00:04:54.705 --> 00:04:59.943
in a moment of silence as we quiet
our hearts in prayer in a posture

00:04:59.943 --> 00:05:04.808
of thankfulness for this day and
for the class of 2017.

00:05:12.147 --> 00:05:17.775
Almighty God, we gather today to
celebrate the diligent work and

00:05:17.775 --> 00:05:23.830
the dedication of the Carnegie
Mellon University class of 2017.

00:05:23.830 --> 00:05:28.340
We pause for a moment to give thanks for

00:05:28.340 --> 00:05:31.580
those who have helped these
students achieve this day.

00:05:33.820 --> 00:05:38.955
For the parents, family,
friends, teachers,

00:05:38.955 --> 00:05:47.040
and any others who have been their
providers of support throughout the years.

00:05:49.200 --> 00:05:54.418
We choose this day to be grateful for
the vision and direction

00:05:54.418 --> 00:06:00.470
of those who helped make Carnegie Mellon
the institution it is today.

00:06:00.470 --> 00:06:05.612
We give thanks to the leadership and
the administration, who continue to carry

00:06:05.612 --> 00:06:10.603
on the vision of having a transformative
impact on society through continual

00:06:10.603 --> 00:06:15.691
innovation in education, research,
creativity, and entrepreneurship.

00:06:18.379 --> 00:06:21.851
Continue to teach these students,
and us as well,

00:06:21.851 --> 00:06:24.290
to look with compassion on others.

00:06:26.320 --> 00:06:32.950
Take away any arrogance or
hatred that may impact our view of others.

00:06:34.590 --> 00:06:37.550
Give us the grace and
ability to love our neighbors and

00:06:37.550 --> 00:06:40.510
to seek justice and
peace in all areas of life.

00:06:42.470 --> 00:06:47.540
Bless these students as they enter
the next stages of their lives and

00:06:47.540 --> 00:06:48.970
seek to reach their full potential.

00:06:51.070 --> 00:06:56.050
Be with them as they take steps into
the known and into the unknown.

00:06:58.270 --> 00:07:01.550
May all that they do, and
the decisions that they make,

00:07:01.550 --> 00:07:06.180
honor you and the tradition of
Carnegie Mellon University.

00:07:06.180 --> 00:07:10.741
We send them forth to impact
society in transformative ways,

00:07:10.741 --> 00:07:15.927
through their work, through their lives,
and their partnerships.

00:07:17.932 --> 00:07:22.530
Be with us this day and
let these students bring You glory.

00:07:22.530 --> 00:07:25.751
Our heart is in the work.

00:07:25.751 --> 00:07:28.322
Amen.

00:07:28.322 --> 00:07:35.820
&gt;&gt; [APPLAUSE]

00:07:46.007 --> 00:07:47.884
&gt;&gt; Good morning, everyone!

00:07:47.884 --> 00:07:53.299
&gt;&gt; [APPLAUSE]
&gt;&gt; It's a good day for the graduates.

00:07:53.299 --> 00:07:56.727
Whoo!

00:07:56.727 --> 00:08:01.270
On behalf of the Board of Trustees,
Let me welcome you to the 120th

00:08:01.270 --> 00:08:04.060
Commencement of
Carnegie Mellon University.

00:08:04.060 --> 00:08:08.335
My name is Jim Rohr, and
it's my honor and pleasure to serve as

00:08:08.335 --> 00:08:13.122
the Board Chairman for
the 2017 Carnegie Mellon Commencement.

00:08:13.122 --> 00:08:16.060
To all the students who
are graduating today,

00:08:16.060 --> 00:08:20.610
let me begin by congratulating
you on your achievement.

00:08:20.610 --> 00:08:24.649
This degree represents years of
hard work and self discipline,

00:08:24.649 --> 00:08:27.876
of discovery and
creativity and problem solving.

00:08:27.876 --> 00:08:30.670
I hope it has a little
fun included as well.

00:08:32.390 --> 00:08:37.183
At Carnegie Mellon, a degree is
a sign that you have surpassed a high

00:08:37.183 --> 00:08:41.402
standard of accomplishment in science,
art, and ideas.

00:08:41.402 --> 00:08:44.803
And that you are ready to use
this knowledge in your lives and

00:08:44.803 --> 00:08:46.380
your future professions.

00:08:47.440 --> 00:08:49.870
You are ready to take on the charge

00:08:49.870 --> 00:08:54.690
of continuing the long standing tradition
of doing the work that matters.

00:08:55.800 --> 00:08:57.594
Congratulations to you all.

00:08:57.600 --> 00:09:04.940
&gt;&gt; [APPLAUSE]

00:09:04.940 --> 00:09:12.680
&gt;&gt; I would also like to wish congratulations to the family members, and to the friends, mentors, faculty,

00:09:12.680 --> 00:09:17.700
and staff who also take great pride in
what the graduates have accomplished.

00:09:18.730 --> 00:09:23.140
Graduation from a demanding academic
institution like Carnegie Mellon

00:09:23.140 --> 00:09:23.980
is a team effort.

00:09:24.980 --> 00:09:27.272
These students couldn't
have done it without you.

00:09:27.272 --> 00:09:31.725
So I invite all of us to thank the support
team with a wonderful round of applause

00:09:31.725 --> 00:09:32.948
for the supporters.

00:09:32.948 --> 00:09:39.890
&gt;&gt; [APPLAUSE]

00:09:39.890 --> 00:09:43.551
&gt;&gt; Now with us today at our 120th
Commencement are some faculty and

00:09:43.551 --> 00:09:47.640
students from Carnegie Mellon's
other locations around the world.

00:09:48.730 --> 00:09:54.601
I am particularly pleased to welcome
students from the CMU Silicon Valley

00:09:54.601 --> 00:09:59.634
campus, and all the way from
Rwanda in our CMU Africa program.

00:09:59.640 --> 00:10:03.575
And also our first to Lakshmi Subramanian

00:10:03.580 --> 00:10:08.490
CMU's Africa Student
Excellence Award Scholars.

00:10:08.490 --> 00:10:10.520
We are delighted to have
you here with us today.

00:10:11.540 --> 00:10:14.420
As members of
the Carnegie Mellon community,

00:10:14.420 --> 00:10:18.490
you are ambassadors of our distinguished,
distinctive university.

00:10:18.490 --> 00:10:22.853
It was at Carnegie Mellon that you gained
solid grounding in your major field.

00:10:22.853 --> 00:10:27.271
And it was at Carnegie Mellon that you
collaborated with people whose backgrounds

00:10:27.271 --> 00:10:30.140
were very different from your own.

00:10:30.140 --> 00:10:35.420
And it was at Carnegie Mellon that you
discovered new ideas about the world,

00:10:35.420 --> 00:10:37.320
and, actually,
new aspects about yourselves.

00:10:38.700 --> 00:10:43.350
As trustees, it's our job to uphold
the university's values, and

00:10:43.350 --> 00:10:46.720
help CMU achieve further excellence
in fulfillment of those values.

00:10:47.810 --> 00:10:51.450
Many trustees are here on
the platform this morning, and

00:10:51.450 --> 00:10:53.980
I would like them to stand and
be recognized.

00:10:53.980 --> 00:10:54.556
Trustees?

00:10:54.556 --> 00:11:04.556
&gt;&gt; [APPLAUSE]

00:11:07.932 --> 00:11:10.108
&gt;&gt; This year, Carnegie Mellon has added to

00:11:10.108 --> 00:11:13.374
its impressive momentum with
a number of new initiatives and

00:11:13.374 --> 00:11:17.550
partnerships that are contributing to
the growth of knowledge in the world.

00:11:17.550 --> 00:11:22.216
And we're moving forward rapidly with
distinctive and collaborative education,

00:11:22.216 --> 00:11:26.422
ambitious research programs in areas
ranging from energy, data science,

00:11:26.422 --> 00:11:29.660
workings of the brain, and
even the science of learning.

00:11:30.820 --> 00:11:34.822
The campus footprint is growing,
with plans fully underway for

00:11:34.822 --> 00:11:38.898
spectacular new spaces designed
to make CMU a standard setter for

00:11:38.898 --> 00:11:41.357
the 21st century higher education.

00:11:41.357 --> 00:11:46.694
With emphasis on collaboration
fields across the enterprise,

00:11:46.694 --> 00:11:50.855
create problem solving,
as well as innovation.

00:11:50.855 --> 00:11:55.462
But behind all of this growth and
expansion is our dynamic president,

00:11:55.462 --> 00:12:00.616
who joined the university in 2013
from the National Science Foundation,

00:12:00.616 --> 00:12:04.925
and who has already had a tremendous
effect on this institution.

00:12:04.925 --> 00:12:08.402
It's my great privilege to
introduce the ninth president of

00:12:08.402 --> 00:12:11.345
Carnegie Mellon University,
Dr. Subra Suresh.

00:12:11.345 --> 00:12:20.471
&gt;&gt; [APPLAUSE]

00:12:20.471 --> 00:12:22.211
&gt;&gt; Good morning.

00:12:22.211 --> 00:12:24.997
&gt;&gt; Good morning.

00:12:24.997 --> 00:12:29.510
&gt;&gt; Good morning everyone and
congratulations graduates.

00:12:29.510 --> 00:12:32.378
I'm going to be saying that a few times.

00:12:32.378 --> 00:12:36.808
Commencement is always a special day for

00:12:36.808 --> 00:12:40.600
family, friends, and faculty.

00:12:40.600 --> 00:12:45.023
But more than anything
else it is a milestone for

00:12:45.023 --> 00:12:50.013
each of you, the graduates,
the class of 2017.

00:12:50.013 --> 00:12:56.804
We are here to celebrate your
accomplishments over the past four years.

00:12:56.804 --> 00:12:59.955
Or five years if you're from
the School of Architecture.

00:12:59.955 --> 00:13:06.515
&gt;&gt; [APPLAUSE]
&gt;&gt; You worked hard to get here,

00:13:06.515 --> 00:13:12.637
and we are very proud and
honored to salute you today.

00:13:12.637 --> 00:13:16.238
Let me also express my
deep appreciation for

00:13:16.238 --> 00:13:20.813
the Carnegie Mellon University Board
of Trustees, and

00:13:20.813 --> 00:13:24.412
to the Chairman of the Board,
Jim Rohr, for

00:13:24.412 --> 00:13:29.401
all their energy, vision,
friendship and leadership.

00:13:29.401 --> 00:13:37.083
With their help,
CMU is poised to have a bright future.

00:13:37.083 --> 00:13:39.358
Thank you, Jim, and thank you, trustees.

00:13:39.358 --> 00:13:45.596
&gt;&gt; [APPLAUSE]

00:13:45.596 --> 00:13:51.003
&gt;&gt; I would like to also recognize a number
of alumni groups in attendance today.

00:13:51.003 --> 00:13:56.891
The 2017 Distinguished Alumni Award
honorees,

00:13:56.891 --> 00:14:02.530
the class of 1967 50th reunion celebrants.

00:14:02.530 --> 00:14:08.734
And, of course, our legacy families.

00:14:08.734 --> 00:14:13.765
Just to give you an idea,
yesterday morning when

00:14:13.765 --> 00:14:21.017
we met with the 50th reunion class,
a number of things had changed.

00:14:21.017 --> 00:14:25.001
A postage stamp was 5 cents in 1967,

00:14:25.001 --> 00:14:30.848
today it's 49 cents, and
it says forever if you can believe it.

00:14:30.848 --> 00:14:38.881
Carnegie Mellon's endowment at that time
was $75 million, it's much greater now.

00:14:38.881 --> 00:14:43.366
There are many, many more things
that have happened since '67, but

00:14:43.366 --> 00:14:47.925
the best news of all is that,
with every incoming class, the quality and

00:14:47.925 --> 00:14:52.490
impact of Carnegie Mellon education
has increased substantially, and

00:14:52.490 --> 00:14:55.602
you represent the very
best of Carnegie Mellon.

00:14:55.602 --> 00:14:58.716
&gt;&gt; [APPLAUSE]
&gt;&gt; Thank you.

00:14:58.720 --> 00:15:03.380
&gt;&gt; [APPLAUSE]

00:15:03.380 --> 00:15:07.420
&gt;&gt; CMU is a beloved tradition in so
many families, and we are also

00:15:07.430 --> 00:15:11.880
pleased to see successive generations
of family members attending CMU.

00:15:13.170 --> 00:15:15.950
All CMU alumni here today

00:15:15.950 --> 00:15:19.620
are specially designated by
the blue stoles they are wearing.

00:15:20.770 --> 00:15:23.240
We are happy to see so
many of you back here.

00:15:23.240 --> 00:15:29.084
Would all CMU alumni in attendance
please stand and be recognized?

00:15:29.084 --> 00:15:39.084
&gt;&gt; [APPLAUSE]

00:15:42.850 --> 00:15:45.687
&gt;&gt; It's wonderful to have you here, and

00:15:45.687 --> 00:15:50.032
I hope our new graduates today
continue this tradition and

00:15:50.032 --> 00:15:52.968
return to Commencement in the future.

00:15:52.968 --> 00:15:58.930
One alumna who our new graduates
should get to know Is our

00:15:58.930 --> 00:16:05.440
Alumni Association Board President Debbie
Yue, Dietrich College Class of 1989.

00:16:05.440 --> 00:16:11.550
Debbie joined
the Alumni Association Board in 2010 and

00:16:11.550 --> 00:16:13.370
began her term nearly a year ago.

00:16:14.490 --> 00:16:17.670
While she was earning her Bachelor's
degree in Technical Writing at

00:16:17.670 --> 00:16:21.680
Carnegie Mellon,
she was a reporter for the Tartan and

00:16:21.680 --> 00:16:23.640
was active in the pre-law society.

00:16:24.930 --> 00:16:29.830
Now a partner at the firm of
Gallagher Sharp in Cleveland, Ohio, Debbie

00:16:29.830 --> 00:16:34.310
has been an active volunteer for the
Northeast Ohio Alumni Networks since 2007.

00:16:34.310 --> 00:16:38.730
Having served previously
as network president.

00:16:38.730 --> 00:16:42.690
She also volunteers as a Carnegie Mellon
admission interviewer and

00:16:42.690 --> 00:16:46.710
is active in a number of professional and
community organizations.

00:16:48.240 --> 00:16:50.440
And since taking office,

00:16:50.440 --> 00:16:54.640
she's been an outstanding representative
of all Carnegie Mellon alumni.

00:16:54.640 --> 00:16:59.370
I would like to invite Debbie
now to the podium, Debbie.

00:16:59.370 --> 00:17:05.240
&gt;&gt; [APPLAUSE]

00:17:05.240 --> 00:17:10.660
&gt;&gt; Thank you, President Suresh, and
congratulations to the Class of 2017 and

00:17:10.663 --> 00:17:14.490
welcome to the Carnegie Mellon
alumni family.

00:17:14.490 --> 00:17:16.619
As you begin the next
chapter of your lives,

00:17:18.490 --> 00:17:23.900
please remember that you are now lifelong
members of the Carnegie Mellon community.

00:17:23.900 --> 00:17:28.090
Therefore, wear your Carnegie Mellon
clothing, bring your CMU mugs to work and

00:17:28.090 --> 00:17:30.730
be proud to be part of
such an amazing group.

00:17:32.050 --> 00:17:35.900
Although Carnegie Mellon alums make up
only a small percentage of the world's

00:17:35.900 --> 00:17:41.310
population, our contributions are great,
and our impact enormous.

00:17:41.310 --> 00:17:46.000
We just celebrated the achievement in
service of a few of our dedicated and

00:17:46.000 --> 00:17:50.440
talented alums at the alumni
awards ceremony on Friday

00:17:50.440 --> 00:17:53.130
and I was inspired not only
by their achievement, but

00:17:53.130 --> 00:17:58.640
by their incredible passion for Carnegie
Mellon, even 60 years after graduation.

00:17:59.910 --> 00:18:02.380
No matter where your
life path will take you,

00:18:02.380 --> 00:18:07.140
you will find Carnegie Mellon alums in
over 149 countries around the world.

00:18:07.140 --> 00:18:10.770
We are leading communities, companies and

00:18:10.770 --> 00:18:14.330
industries and
we are making the world a better place.

00:18:15.960 --> 00:18:19.890
Although you are leaving the comforts
of your Carnegie Mellon home,

00:18:19.890 --> 00:18:21.820
remember to always stay true to yourself,

00:18:22.970 --> 00:18:27.700
continue to be intellectually curious and
continue to learn.

00:18:27.700 --> 00:18:31.709
Be supportive of each other as well as for
those who are following in your footsteps.

00:18:33.050 --> 00:18:37.223
And always go outside
of your comfort zone and

00:18:37.223 --> 00:18:40.469
embrace your vision for the future.

00:18:40.469 --> 00:18:43.889
The Carnegie Mellon Alumni Association
provides many ways for

00:18:43.889 --> 00:18:48.224
you to continue to learn and to connect
with each other and with the university.

00:18:48.224 --> 00:18:50.707
In addition to virtual programs,

00:18:50.707 --> 00:18:54.997
we have over 55 active alumni
networks around the world.

00:18:54.997 --> 00:18:58.003
Therefore, as you settle
into your new lives,

00:18:58.003 --> 00:19:01.620
please find your local alumni network and
get involved.

00:19:03.840 --> 00:19:05.530
And as with any family,

00:19:05.530 --> 00:19:11.110
I wish that you will come back to visit
often, stay in touch, and think of us.

00:19:11.110 --> 00:19:13.619
We wish you nothing but
the best and brightest future.

00:19:14.630 --> 00:19:18.300
On behalf of the Carnegie Mellon
Alumni Association and Board,

00:19:18.300 --> 00:19:23.075
it is my distinct pleasure to welcome you
into the Carnegie Mellon alumni family.

00:19:23.075 --> 00:19:27.036
Congratulations, Class of 2017.

00:19:27.036 --> 00:19:36.780
&gt;&gt; [APPLAUSE]
&gt;&gt; Thank you very much, Debbie.

00:19:38.130 --> 00:19:45.690
Our student speaker today, is one
of 129 students from 30 countries and

00:19:45.690 --> 00:19:52.380
75 universities chosen this academic
year as a Schwarzman Scholar.

00:19:53.510 --> 00:19:57.630
Today, Krystal Thomas earns her bachelor's
degree in biological sciences from

00:19:57.630 --> 00:20:00.745
Carnegie Mellon University's
Mellon College of Science.

00:20:00.745 --> 00:20:08.180
&gt;&gt; [APPLAUSE]
&gt;&gt; Krystal has been an active

00:20:08.180 --> 00:20:13.400
member of the Carnegie Mellon community,
serving as founding president of Colors at

00:20:13.400 --> 00:20:19.810
CMU, a student organization that promotes
open conversations on race and diversity.

00:20:20.930 --> 00:20:26.270
She served as one of the inaugural members
of the Diversity and Inclusion Roundtable,

00:20:26.270 --> 00:20:30.580
and is a mentor in the Coaching Minority
Progress and Success in Science program.

00:20:31.730 --> 00:20:35.170
She's a past president of the Gates
Millennium Scholarship from the Bill and

00:20:35.170 --> 00:20:36.469
Melinda Gates Foundation.

00:20:37.660 --> 00:20:41.040
And is an Andrew Carnegie Society Scholar,

00:20:41.040 --> 00:20:45.430
a distinction bestowed upon
only 40 graduating seniors.

00:20:46.880 --> 00:20:48.880
The daughter of a Haitian immigrant,

00:20:50.060 --> 00:20:54.220
Crystal plans to complete a Master of
Global Affairs with a concentration in

00:20:54.220 --> 00:20:59.218
public policy at Shanghai University
in Beijing, China and

00:20:59.218 --> 00:21:04.310
work to address barriers to healthcare
faced by immigrant families.

00:21:04.310 --> 00:21:09.407
It was a great pleasure for
me this morning to meet Crystal's parents.

00:21:09.407 --> 00:21:11.850
Crystal, I would like to now
invite you to the podium.

00:21:11.850 --> 00:21:22.122
&gt;&gt; [APPLAUSE]

00:21:22.122 --> 00:21:22.975
&gt;&gt; Hi everyone.

00:21:27.626 --> 00:21:31.390
Five years ago,
I came to CMU as a high school student.

00:21:32.800 --> 00:21:35.940
I was here for the university's
Summer Academy of Math and

00:21:35.940 --> 00:21:38.400
Science or SAMS for short.

00:21:40.150 --> 00:21:44.420
Now, I didn't know that Carnegie Mellon,
or that SAMS,

00:21:44.420 --> 00:21:48.020
excuse me, was a program for
minority students.

00:21:48.020 --> 00:21:51.830
And the entire time, I was surrounded
by people who look like me.

00:21:53.100 --> 00:21:56.200
So I left thinking, this is great.

00:21:56.200 --> 00:22:01.035
Carnegie Mellon University, a historically
black college for math and science, right?

00:22:01.035 --> 00:22:03.105
&gt;&gt; [LAUGH]
&gt;&gt; I'm totally going here.

00:22:08.417 --> 00:22:14.292
[LAUGH] Even though CMU wasn't
exactly what I expected,

00:22:14.292 --> 00:22:18.670
I'm still so glad I decided to come here.

00:22:18.670 --> 00:22:21.730
I have learned so

00:22:21.730 --> 00:22:27.192
much while here at Carnegie Melon,
and not just academically.

00:22:27.192 --> 00:22:32.020
Problem solving,
how to hold difficult conversations,

00:22:33.450 --> 00:22:39.130
and most importantly, I now know there's
still so much more that I don't know.

00:22:41.140 --> 00:22:42.140
What drives people?

00:22:42.140 --> 00:22:45.010
How do our environments influence us?

00:22:46.540 --> 00:22:49.380
How is our world interconnected?

00:22:49.380 --> 00:22:52.580
I've started to think
about these questions,

00:22:52.580 --> 00:22:56.580
because I've been fortunate
enough to meet many of you.

00:22:56.580 --> 00:23:01.120
And getting to know your stories,
your perspectives and

00:23:01.132 --> 00:23:06.495
the way you think about things,
