it's a pretty good day for
your wallets as well.

00:44:07.292 --> 00:44:11.810
Congratulations for having traveled
this journey with your children.

00:44:11.810 --> 00:44:15.900
A journey that began not with their
enrollment at this university, but

00:44:15.900 --> 00:44:18.360
at the moment of their birth.

00:44:18.540 --> 00:44:20.880
Whether your children fully realized it or

00:44:20.880 --> 00:44:27.060
not, whether they have fully expressed
it to you or not, and they will.

00:44:27.280 --> 00:44:31.860
They would not be here today
without your love and support and

00:44:31.864 --> 00:44:34.202
encouragement along the way.

00:44:34.202 --> 00:44:36.203
So congratulations to the parents.

00:44:36.203 --> 00:44:43.530
&gt;&gt; [APPLAUSE]

00:44:43.530 --> 00:44:46.840
&gt;&gt; Most important to the class of 2017,

00:44:46.840 --> 00:44:49.240
congratulations.

00:44:49.240 --> 00:44:53.180
Graduating from college is
an impressive achievement, but

00:44:53.180 --> 00:44:57.690
especially graduating from one of
the leading universities in the world,

00:44:57.690 --> 00:45:02.880
an institution characterized by
high standards and excellence.

00:45:03.060 --> 00:45:06.620
One that has produced
winners of Nobel Prizes, and

00:45:06.620 --> 00:45:11.900
Turing, Tony, Emmy, and
Academy Award winners.

00:45:12.300 --> 00:45:17.380
Carnegie Mellon University has
prepared you for a life of purpose and

00:45:17.385 --> 00:45:22.770
meaning, and there are people and
moments you will never forget.

00:45:22.770 --> 00:45:27.720
Including, I understand,
the Spring Carnival, which includes what

00:45:27.720 --> 00:45:34.740
I gather are some pretty amazing amusement
park rides, booths, and buggy races.

00:45:35.020 --> 00:45:39.360
To bag piping, which the school
has made into an art form,

00:45:39.377 --> 00:45:43.482
and to my personal favorite,
the Band Without Pants.

00:45:43.482 --> 00:45:47.979
&gt;&gt; [APPLAUSE]
&gt;&gt; A tradition unique to Carnegie Mellon,

00:45:47.979 --> 00:45:51.734
and I'm confident I can say one
you are unlikely to encounter

00:45:51.740 --> 00:45:54.700
in your first full-time job.

00:45:56.060 --> 00:46:01.360
You are graduating at a moment of
great challenge for our nation.

00:46:01.360 --> 00:46:06.670
When our country will decide on matters
having to do not with just commerce,

00:46:06.670 --> 00:46:08.420
but conscience.

00:46:08.600 --> 00:46:13.620
Not just with what we will gain,
but what we will give.

00:46:13.880 --> 00:46:19.640
Not just with our military power,
but with our deepest ideals.

00:46:19.940 --> 00:46:24.400
This is hardly the most difficult
moment in American history.

00:46:24.640 --> 00:46:29.640
I believe you can safely argue that
the Civil War, two World Wars,

00:46:29.642 --> 00:46:33.587
and the Great Depression
have us beat by a long shot.

00:46:33.587 --> 00:46:36.665
You are a blessed generation in so
many ways,

00:46:36.665 --> 00:46:41.220
with opportunities unimaginable
to past generations.

00:46:41.220 --> 00:46:45.960
And gratitude is one of
the hallmarks of a fulfilled life.

00:46:46.160 --> 00:46:51.600
But every life has hardships,
every generation faces obstacles.

00:46:51.619 --> 00:46:56.515
And we are in the midst of
a profoundly important moment

00:46:56.515 --> 00:47:00.462
in the political and
civic life of America.

00:47:00.462 --> 00:47:05.440
The challenges today are more
from within than without.

00:47:05.440 --> 00:47:10.139
And I believe this is a moment that,
if we do not handle it well,

00:47:10.139 --> 00:47:15.018
could produce harmful effects on
my generation and on yours, and

00:47:15.018 --> 00:47:17.169
on generations yet unborn.

00:47:17.169 --> 00:47:20.440
The stakes are that serious.

00:47:20.600 --> 00:47:26.060
So today I wanna speak about some
disturbing trends in our national life.

00:47:26.260 --> 00:47:30.660
Trends that need to be challenged
by people of both genders,

00:47:30.660 --> 00:47:35.320
every class, race, and ethnic background.

00:47:35.960 --> 00:47:41.220
Of every political party and ideology,
but most especially by young people.

00:47:41.620 --> 00:47:48.020
Who are not only inheritors of the future,
but will do so much to shape it.

00:47:48.022 --> 00:47:53.483
The first disturbing trend I want
to mention is the attack on truth.

00:47:53.483 --> 00:47:58.249
There are many people these days,
including people at the highest level in

00:47:58.249 --> 00:48:02.525
public life-
&gt;&gt; [APPLAUSE]

00:48:02.525 --> 00:48:07.967
[APPLAUSE]

00:48:07.967 --> 00:48:12.400
&gt;&gt; Who use lies to devalue truth.

00:48:12.540 --> 00:48:16.320
Those who are part of this effort
like describing what's happening

00:48:16.330 --> 00:48:20.685
euphemistically using phrases
like alternative facts.

00:48:20.685 --> 00:48:25.488
&gt;&gt; [APPLAUSE]
&gt;&gt; But we know better to paraphrase

00:48:25.488 --> 00:48:31.872
Shakespeare's Juliet,
a lie by any other name is still a lie.

00:48:31.872 --> 00:48:35.524
&gt;&gt; [LAUGH]

00:48:35.524 --> 00:48:40.390
[APPLAUSE]

00:48:40.390 --> 00:48:41.400
&gt;&gt; What is so

00:48:41.400 --> 00:48:46.470
striking is the brazenness and
rapidity of the lies and their purpose

00:48:46.470 --> 00:48:52.260
Which is to de-legitimize sources of
information hostile to those in power.

00:48:52.360 --> 00:48:57.020
The lies tumble down like
rocks in an avalanche.

00:48:57.140 --> 00:49:03.420
They are not subtle, they are overt,
obvious, and part of a conscious effort.

00:49:03.580 --> 00:49:08.692
Language is being employed not to
reveal reality, but to obscure it,

00:49:08.700 --> 00:49:13.390
not to simply mislead people but
to disorient them,

00:49:13.390 --> 00:49:19.640
to assert power over truth in
an effort to deconstruct it.

00:49:19.780 --> 00:49:23.400
So here's why this should matter to you.

00:49:23.560 --> 00:49:29.320
If we do not share a common reality,
we can't reason together.

00:49:29.320 --> 00:49:33.100
Truth creates restraints on power.

00:49:33.320 --> 00:49:39.010
If we allow those with power to
control the very idea of truth itself,

00:49:39.010 --> 00:49:43.420
then we cannot identify and
stand against injustice.

00:49:43.560 --> 00:49:46.780
And if we can't identify injustice,

00:49:46.786 --> 00:49:52.313
then we cannot replace it with
concepts like equality under law,

00:49:52.313 --> 00:49:57.149
respect, decency, compassion,
and justice itself.

00:49:57.149 --> 00:50:05.790
&gt;&gt; [APPLAUSE]

00:50:05.790 --> 00:50:08.330
&gt;&gt; A great university is always enlisted

00:50:08.330 --> 00:50:13.710
against the spread of illusion, and on the
side of reality, said President Kennedy.

00:50:13.710 --> 00:50:18.840
And that is the essence of your calling
as graduates of a great university.

00:50:18.980 --> 00:50:24.340
My encouragement to you is to be women and
men who stand for truth.

00:50:24.460 --> 00:50:29.460
Who spend your life in search of it,
even if you never fully know it.

00:50:29.480 --> 00:50:33.420
Who believe in inquiries,
in facts, in objective reality.

00:50:33.423 --> 00:50:38.114
And who have the courage to speak
truth to power even when there may be

00:50:38.114 --> 00:50:39.465
a cost to doing so.

00:50:39.465 --> 00:50:49.013
&gt;&gt; [APPLAUSE]
&gt;&gt; If you do,

00:50:49.013 --> 00:50:54.390
if you are defenders of truth in an age
marked by lies, it will have a liberating

00:50:54.390 --> 00:51:01.680
effect on our fellow citizens and make
more possible all good things in life.

00:51:01.880 --> 00:51:06.820
A second truth that needs to be
confronted is the attack on free speech.

00:51:06.940 --> 00:51:09.780
&gt;&gt; In the last several years,-
&gt;&gt; [APPLAUSE]

00:51:09.788 --> 00:51:11.805
&gt;&gt; We have seen a powerful movement,

00:51:11.805 --> 00:51:15.030
one that seeks to shut down free speech,

00:51:15.030 --> 00:51:18.280
gain traction in the academy.

00:51:18.380 --> 00:51:22.000
The very institutions that were
created in order to allow for

00:51:22.000 --> 00:51:24.860
the free exchange of ideas.

00:51:24.960 --> 00:51:29.150
On some campuses,
we've seen certain speakers not invited.

00:51:29.150 --> 00:51:31.220
On others, they've been shouted down.

00:51:31.220 --> 00:51:34.480
And on still others,
we are witnessing violence.

00:51:34.640 --> 00:51:39.940
Now I understand this kind of thing isn't
happening on most American campuses, but

00:51:39.940 --> 00:51:43.740
it's happening in too many places and
it needs to end.

00:51:44.020 --> 00:51:46.800
But there's something
else going on as well.

00:51:46.800 --> 00:51:50.720
College students are increasingly
demanding protection from words and

00:51:50.720 --> 00:51:53.090
speech they find offensive.

00:51:53.090 --> 00:51:57.610
We hear a lot about trigger warnings and
safe spaces which are designed to

00:51:57.610 --> 00:52:03.340
protect students from viewpoints that
they might find upsetting and unsettling.

00:52:03.480 --> 00:52:06.200
Here's why I think this is problematic.

00:52:06.200 --> 00:52:11.940
For one thing, I don't think most of you
want to be treated like porcelain dolls.

00:52:12.100 --> 00:52:15.450
And now that you are college graduates,
the rest of the world and

00:52:15.450 --> 00:52:19.120
certainly the business world
won't treat you that way.

00:52:19.120 --> 00:52:23.460
So no one is doing college students
any favors when they intellectually

00:52:23.460 --> 00:52:24.465
isolate them.

00:52:24.465 --> 00:52:33.270
&gt;&gt; [APPLAUSE]
&gt;&gt; But

00:52:33.270 --> 00:52:37.140
the issue extends beyond the walls of
the academy and matters whether or

00:52:37.140 --> 00:52:41.040
not you ever step foot on a campus again.

00:52:41.140 --> 00:52:45.820
While many of you are about to
complete your formal education, you will

00:52:45.830 --> 00:52:51.860
spend a lifetime continuing to learn,
gathering and processing new information

00:52:51.860 --> 00:52:56.900
and dealing with people with different
life experiences and points of view.

00:52:56.900 --> 00:53:02.240
Shutting down free speech, insulating
ourselves from hearing competing points of

00:53:02.244 --> 00:53:07.495
view is the equivalent of injecting poison
into the bloodstream of our republic.

00:53:07.495 --> 00:53:14.610
&gt;&gt; [APPLAUSE]

00:53:14.610 --> 00:53:18.880
&gt;&gt; John Stewart Mill in his 1859 classic,

00:53:18.880 --> 00:53:22.670
On Liberty,
put it as well as anyone ever has.

00:53:22.670 --> 00:53:28.050
And I quote,
he who knows only his own side of the case

00:53:28.050 --> 00:53:31.280
knows little of that, Mill wrote.

00:53:31.280 --> 00:53:36.280
His reason may be good and
no one may have been able to refute that.

00:53:36.280 --> 00:53:41.720
But if he is equally unable to refute
the reasons on the opposite side,

00:53:41.860 --> 00:53:46.450
if he does not so much as know what
they are, he has no ground for

00:53:46.450 --> 00:53:49.520
preferring either opinion.

00:53:49.640 --> 00:53:52.740
Mill went on to say this, nor is it enough

00:53:52.740 --> 00:53:57.580
that he should hear the opinions of
adversaries from his own teachers

00:53:57.580 --> 00:53:59.690
presented as they state them and

00:53:59.690 --> 00:54:03.210
accompanied by what they
offer as refutations.

00:54:03.210 --> 00:54:07.460
He must be able to hear from
persons who actually believe them.

00:54:07.460 --> 00:54:12.740
He must know them in their most
plausible and persuasive form.

00:54:13.080 --> 00:54:17.390
So my encouragement to you is to be
the men and women who stand up for

00:54:17.390 --> 00:54:20.010
free speech, who welcome debate.

00:54:20.010 --> 00:54:23.980
Who model for
others what genuine dialogue is, and

00:54:23.980 --> 00:54:26.990
who are not afraid to have
your beliefs challenged.

00:54:28.220 --> 00:54:34.020
Too many of us live in intellectual silos,
where we seek out people and

00:54:34.020 --> 00:54:38.850
information that simply
reinforces our existing opinions.

00:54:38.850 --> 00:54:42.100
Venture out of those silos.

00:54:42.100 --> 00:54:45.760
We are better when we are exposed
to different ideas and

00:54:45.760 --> 00:54:48.220
competing philosophies.

00:54:48.980 --> 00:54:54.640
Learn to listen in order to understand
others, not just to respond to them.

00:54:54.649 --> 00:54:57.801
And remain open to
the possibility that you may have

00:54:57.801 --> 00:55:00.840
something to learn from others.

00:55:00.840 --> 00:55:04.510
Be the generation that
embodies real tolerance,

00:55:04.510 --> 00:55:09.130
genuine inquiry and
authentic open mindedness.

00:55:09.130 --> 00:55:14.969
It is what this nation desperately needs
during this fractured and fractious time.

00:55:14.969 --> 00:55:24.370
&gt;&gt; [APPLAUSE]
&gt;&gt; The third

00:55:24.370 --> 00:55:28.780
trend that needs to be confronted
is the attack on civility.

00:55:28.860 --> 00:55:32.910
We live in an age of
escalating incivility.

00:55:32.910 --> 00:55:37.700
We see it all around us,
on our roads, in airways,

00:55:37.700 --> 00:55:42.870
in sports stadiums, and
on social media, and in politics.

00:55:42.870 --> 00:55:47.840
The problem has gotten worse recently,
with those running for high public office

00:55:47.840 --> 00:55:53.750
mocking reporters and demeaning
opponents with childish names or worse.

00:55:53.750 --> 00:55:55.460
It seems that no words,

00:55:55.460 --> 00:56:00.840
no matter how hurtful or cruel to
others are considered inappropriate.

00:56:00.980 --> 00:56:07.400
We are fostering the conditions in which
we view others not as opponents, but enemies.

00:56:07.460 --> 00:56:10.210
We're treating one another as subhuman and

00:56:10.210 --> 00:56:14.980
that's a terribly,
dangerous line to cross.

00:56:15.120 --> 00:56:21.620
Civility is more than nice manners, it's
a precondition of democratic dialogue,

00:56:21.620 --> 00:56:26.360
in the words of Professor Steven L. Carter
of Yale Law School.

00:56:26.520 --> 00:56:32.200
Civility is part of the, quote,
etiquette of democracy, unquote.

00:56:32.200 --> 00:56:36.330
It allows for genuine social interaction.

00:56:36.330 --> 00:56:40.550
It's been said that the true
genius of Martin Luther King Jr.

00:56:40.550 --> 00:56:46.240
was not his ability to argue
the pain of an oppressed people, but

00:56:46.240 --> 00:56:52.580
his ability to inspire those very people
to be loving and civil in their descent.

00:56:52.720 --> 00:56:57.270
We should treat each other with civility,
not because we agree with others, but

00:56:57.270 --> 00:57:01.800
because it is a measure of our respect for
human dignity.

00:57:01.960 --> 00:57:04.130
It's what we owe all people,

00:57:04.130 --> 00:57:08.510
including those with whom we
have fierce disagreements.

00:57:08.510 --> 00:57:11.020
Our institutions, our culture,

00:57:11.020 --> 00:57:16.600
our communities cannot be sustained let
alone thrive if civility is eroded.

00:57:16.600 --> 00:57:20.305
It is an essential democratic virtue.

00:57:20.305 --> 00:57:31.500
[APPLAUSE]
&gt;&gt; Kingman Brewster, a former president of Yale,

00:57:31.580 --> 00:57:37.040
said, quote, the presumption of
innocence is not just a legal concept.

00:57:37.050 --> 00:57:41.420
In commonplace terms,
it rests on the generosity of spirit

00:57:41.420 --> 00:57:45.840
which assumes the best,
not the worst of a stranger.

00:57:45.920 --> 00:57:50.620
My encouragement to you is to be
the women and men who embody civility,

00:57:50.620 --> 00:57:56.620
who demonstrate a generosity of
spirit in an ungenerous time.

00:57:56.740 --> 00:58:03.660
And who assume the best, not the worst,
of the stranger, of those you do not know,

00:58:03.660 --> 00:58:07.940
people whose life experiences
are different than yours, and

00:58:07.940 --> 00:58:12.940
who may see the world in a dramatically
different way than you do.

00:58:13.060 --> 00:58:18.740
In doing so, you will make us
a more decent and just society.

00:58:19.680 --> 00:58:23.500
This country desperately needs
the skills you have developed

00:58:23.500 --> 00:58:26.210
during your years at Carnegie Mellon.

00:58:26.210 --> 00:58:31.380
But it needs something more than
your skills, it needs your ideals.

00:58:33.070 --> 00:58:35.630
You leave this great
university as better men and

00:58:35.630 --> 00:58:38.820
women than when you arrived,
more knowledgeable and

00:58:38.820 --> 00:58:44.120
better educated, I'm sure, but
I trust wiser and more hopeful.

00:58:44.460 --> 00:58:48.730
There's a beautiful line by William
Wordsworth in his poem The Prelude,

00:58:48.730 --> 00:58:53.720
in which he says, quote,
what we have loved others will love and

00:58:53.720 --> 00:58:56.000
we will teach them how.

00:58:56.060 --> 00:59:00.660
The faculty at CMU has taught
you what to know and love and

00:59:00.660 --> 00:59:05.540
now it is your turn to teach others
what you have come to know and love.

00:59:06.440 --> 00:59:09.500
I wish you all a life of joy and

00:59:09.500 --> 00:59:14.180
purpose, of success and
fulfillment, and congratulations

00:59:14.240 --> 00:59:16.660
to the great class of 2017.

00:59:16.660 --> 00:59:26.660
Thank you very much.
